irst recorded bearer of the surname is John <i>de Beveresford</i>, who held the manor of Beresford, Staffordshire, from <i>c.</i> 1220 to 1241. All present-day Beresfords are apparently descended from Thomas Beresford, who fought at Agincourt in 1415 and who fathered sixteen sons and five daughters. The Irish branch of the family includes the Marquesses of Waterford."],"variants":[{"name":"Berisford","meanings":["English: variant of   Beresford  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Beresford was born about 1350, in Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England, his father, John de Beresforde, was 41 and his mother, Emma Bagnolde, was 66. He married Cecilia Warren from 1370 to 1380, in Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died after 1411, in England."},"et":{"about 1350–after 1411":"umbes 1350–pärast 1411","1320–1360":"1320–1360","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1350–1408":"1350–1408","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1380–1473":"1380–1473","1390–1475":"1390–1475","1310–1349":"1310–1349","1285–1320":"1285–1320","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1473":"1473","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1349":"1349","1370 to 1380":"1370 kuni 1380","1411":"1411","1310":"1310","1475":"1475","after 1408":"pärast 1408","1320":"1320","1408":"1408","about 1350":"umbes 1350","after 1411":"pärast 1411","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England